solutions.content:
**Brute Force approach - O(n^2) :**
explore all the pairs of vertical lines keeping one pointer(i) at index 0 and other at (i) +1 and increment it .

**Optimized Approach - O(N)- time complexity** 


This is a very classic question of two-pointers. Here i pointer is at 0 and j is at the end i.e. height.size()-1 we are finding the vertical lines which will give us the maximum area. so here two cases will arise:
1) what if increment i pointer 
   a) maybe the height will increase ( than  max water will increase) 
   b) if height decreases - water will decrease.
2) if we decrement in j :
   a) height will increase ( water will decrease ) because we always take the minimum of the heights
   b) height will decrease (water will decrease ) 

so what factor will decide if i will be incremented or j will decrement?
if the height of i is greater than height of j than we will decrement j  because no longer it can give us a max water
if the height of j is greater than height of i vertical lines we will increment i 
if both the vertical lines are the same i & j than whichever can be moved it doesn't effect.


```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxArea(vector<int>& height) {
        int i =0; 
        int j = height.size()-1;
        int max_water = 0;// to store the maximum water collected
        while(i< j){
           int min_height = min(height[i], height[j]); // minimum of the two vertical lines height is responsible for containing the water 
           int width = j-i; // index of j - index of i

           max_water = max(max_water, min_height *width); // update the max_water 
            if(height[i] > height[j]){
              //whichever has the minimum height will move
                j--;
            }else{
                i++; // if i has minimum height we will increment it or both i and j pointers have same height increment i it dosen't effect even we can decrement j also for the equal heights 
            }

        }
        return max_water;
    }
};
```
