# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
here are the 3 things which came to my mind when read the Question:
1. distance between the two pillers (width) should be maximum to get maximum area. 
2. the minimum height of two pillers will be the height of the container.
3. Only beneficial to process the area if we get high value of height as we move on because we need more area, i.e. ultimately more height and more width.

***Please Upvote if you find it helpful :)***
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
My approach is a two pointer approach with initially one pointer at starting of vector/array and another at the end of the vector/array.

here I have broken the process in some points:
1. we have two pointers i = 0 and j = A.size() - 1.
2. increase the pointer whose value is small i.e., if A[i]<A[j], i++.
3. if the value at new increased pointer is more than the value at the previous pointer, i.e., if A[i]>A[i-1], we will calculate the area by min(A[i],A[j])*(j-i). (here min is taken as min of both will be the height of the container)
4. We will then update the value of area by taking the maximum of present calculated area and previous area using max() function.
5. similarly if A[j]<=A[i], then j--.
6. if A[j]>A[j+1], we'll calculate the area with same formula and update it similarly.
7. We'll continue this till i and j becomes equal.
8. At last we will get maximum possible value of area.

**Go and see the code below for better understanding.**
# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$ , beats  96%
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$ , beats 98%
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


# Code
